<TEXT>
a powerful storm pelted parts of northern 
california on saturday causing power failures and a death by 
lightning and threatening the nations most valuable white wine 
grape harvest 
the storm knocked out electricity from king city 100 miles south 
of san jose to chico about 160 miles north of san francisco said 
pacific gas amp electric co spokesman ron rutkowski 
he said 200000 residents lost power beginning at 5 am mostly 
because of lightning strikes which are unusual in this part of the 
west service was restored in most areas after a few hours 
rutkowski said 
lightning struck and killed a man during a softball game in 
cotati about 40 miles north of san francisco police said 
a train that takes visitors on tours of the famed napa valley 
wine country made its inaugural ride despite being struck by 
lightning and suffering a power failure before leaving the station 
but growers in the area visited by the wine train said the rain 
threatened to cause rot or late maturity for pricey chardonnay and 
sauvignon blanc grapes that are nearly ready for harvest on 21000 
acres in napa and sonoma counties 
it all depends on what happens in the next three of four 
days said grower andrew beckstoffer weve got to get some wind 
and heat to dry things up but if we get humidity these grapes 
will rot 
he said as much as threequarters of the most expensive white 
grapes in the country worth 1800 a ton or more could be lost 
the rains could allow ruinous mold to form on the grapes or 
dilute the grape sugar delaying the maturation process and thereby 
putting the grapes at greater risk of being reached by the rot 
saidjerry luper winemaster at rutherford hill winery 
enologists say the 1989 white grapes of napa and sonoma counties 
have a potential to be a great vintage if the rain doesnt get to 
them first 
the red grapes tougher and thickerskinner than the whites are 
still on the vines and wont be harvested for weeks 
</TEXT>
