<TEXT>
the nations new hightech weather radar system 
has passed its first test and is now headed for a detailed 
evaluation the national weather service announced sunday 
on a scale of 1100 the new radar scored a 91 at detecting 
severe storms in five months of tests at the air force operational 
test and evaluation center in norman okla 
by comparison the nations current weather radar system averaged 
only a 58 on the same types of tests the weather service reports 
nws director elbert w friday jr said he was pleased with the 
results in the tests of nexrad or next generation weather radar 
however he said more performance and reliability testing must be 
done before the system can be installed across the country 
nexrad will begin operational testing in the spring with the 
first system expected to become operational in july at twin lakes 
okla near oklahoma city according to friday 
by the mid1990s the new system is expected to go into service at 
165 locations across the nation the system will be used by the 
weather service federal aviation administration air force and navy 
in addition to improving the ability to forecast tornadoes 
thunderstorms hailstorms and damaging winds the new radars also had 
less than half as many false alarms as the current radar system 
the new radars use what is called doppler technology which 
allows the radar beam to detect not just the presence of rain and 
moisture in the air but also the speed and direction of winds 
radar sends out an electronic impulse and when part of that 
impulse bounces back the machine can determine the location of the 
object causing the reflection 
in the case of doppler radar it can also determine the movement 
of the reflecting item such as a tornado or thunderstorm 
in the tests the new radars were able to detect severe weather as 
far as 250 miles from the site of the equipment officials said 
</TEXT>
